                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d225">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">033.3811/37: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Haiti</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Merrell</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Port au Prince</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1926-07-06T11:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">July 6, 1926—11 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received July 7—noon.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>70. President Borno arrived yesterday and was given a very enthusiastic
                    reception. He stated that he now has more affection than ever for the United
                    States and that he is prepared to cooperate with American officials most loyally
                    in achieving the ends of the treaty, which must be speedily accomplished.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Merrell</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
